snippet.textDisplay:
I can relate so much when Nancy's sister talks about how after Eddie died chris started expressing more dark thoughts about kids being kidnapped etc" because although I wouldn't think about those things specifically, I had alot of dark and morbid thoughts after my best friend committed suicide. The stuff I thought about and looked up online consumed me for a long time.

I believe the tragedy was a combination of losing Eddie and the clear mental health issues/issues with chris's brain.

I do know that when you lose someone very close to you in a tragic way, death isn't as scary. I never thought about suicide before my best friend but after he died it was a real and plausible option for me. It opens the door. I know Eddie didnt kill himself but I suspect the same happened for chris. You tell yourself its an option if the pain is too much to bear.

snippet.textDisplay:
I just want to say that the whole "big guy" thing may have ended up in WCW but it started in WWE and is still a problem. WCW basically introduced most of the world to these guys and their styles through the cruiserweight division.

I was a huge WCW fan from around 96 to 99 from age 10 to 13. Something I remember was that there were certain guys that as soon as you heard their music hit you immediately stopped what you were doing and watched. They were all mid carders or lower and Benoit was one of them. Benoit, Malenko, Guerrero, Juventud, Psychosis the list goes on.

In WCW you watched the main event for the story but you watched the mid card for the some of the best wrestling you've ever seen.

snippet.textDisplay: In this insane time we're living in now, this a flash back of another time where life sat still. This story to me shows nothing but tragedy and comedy, not even Shakespeare himself could have written such a heartfelt scene that would break me to my very core. The legacy of these men are entwined and the horrors that transpired do NOT overshadow my true feelings for both of them. I loved wrestling, but I was by no means a mega fan; I always loved them both and they turned into some of my favorite heros. The Trauma that destroyed Benoit came from dedication and this evil that transpired doesn't represent the man he was and to me that is the biggest tragedy. RIP to all that was lost in this terrible time.

snippet.textDisplay: I remember when Eddie died like it was yesterday. My mom gave me the news, and I thought she was fucking with me. Turned on Raw the next night and I couldn’t believe my eyes and ears! The death of Chris was even more of a shock! Here I am about to watch the scripted memorial for Vince McMahon, only to see “In memory of Chris Benoit” like what?!? The wrestling business was, and will never be the same without these two. I will not celebrate nor forgive the way Chris went out, but I’d be a liar if I said I didn’t miss him in the ring.

snippet.textDisplay:
The general consensus with most people talking about Chris Benoit is that he's a monster. Watching this you kinda get the idea that he was a kind yet deeply damaged person. That Eddie was not only his best friend but his religious mentor and with him gone he seemed to lose the will to live.
My theory is Chris in a mixture of severe depression and brain injury he genuinely thought he'd see Eddie and that he'd be doing a favor for Daniel who was stricken with Fragile X and his wife by bringing them with him to heaven. That he saw it less as murdering them and more as bringing them to paradise to be with God and Eddie.
I think he genuinely thought he was doing something good and his brain warped such an evil act into an act of love.
